Definition 3.2 ([Hir03, Hov99]). Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a category. A model structure on $\mathcal{A}$ consists of three distinguished classes of morphisms $(\mathrm{Cof},\mathrm{W},\mathrm{Fib})$ called cofibrations, weak equivalences and fibrations, respectively, such that the following holds: (MS1) The class $\mathrm{W}$ is closed under retracts. Moreover, if $w_{1},w_{2}$ are two composable morphisms and two of $w_{1},w_{2},w_{2}w_{1}$ belong to $\mathrm{W}$, so does the third. (MS2) The pairs $(\mathrm{Cof}\cap\mathrm{W},\mathrm{Fib})$ and $(\mathrm{Cof},\mathrm{W}\cap\mathrm{Fib})$ are functorial weak factorization systems. The morphisms in $\mathrm{Cof}\cap\mathrm{W}$ are called trivial cofibrations, and the ones in $\mathrm{W}\cap\mathrm{Fib}$ are called trivial fibrations. A model category is a complete and cocomplete category $\mathcal{A}$ together with a model structure $(\mathrm{Cof},\mathrm{W},\mathrm{Fib})$ on it. The homotopy category $\operatorname{Ho}\mathcal{A}$ of $\mathcal{A}$ is the universal category $\mathcal{A}[\mathrm{W}^{-1}]$ obtained from $\mathcal{A}$ by formally inverting all morphisms in $\mathrm{W}$.
Definition 1.16. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a triangulated category with small products. A full subcategory $\mathcal{S}\subseteq\mathcal{T}$ is called cosuspended if $\mathcal{S}$ is closed under taking products, and if $\Sigma^{-1}Z\to X\to Y\to Z$ is a triangle with $Y,Z\in\mathcal{S}$, then $X\in\mathcal{S}$.
Definition 5.1. A prederivator is a strict $2$-functor $\mathbb{D}\colon\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}^{\textrm{op}}\to\mathcal{CAT}$. Here, $\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}$ stands for the $2$-category of all small categories and $\mathcal{CAT}$ for the “$2$-category” of all not necessarily small categories. Our convention for $\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}^{\textrm{op}}$, following [Gro12], is that the direction of $1$-morphisms (functors) is formally inverted and the direction of $2$-morphisms (transformations) is kept. The adjective “strict” refers to the fact that $\mathbb{D}$ is required to preserve the compositions of $1$-morphisms strictly rather than only up to natural equivalence.
Definition 3.7. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a category and $\mathcal{C}\subseteq\mathcal{A}$ be a full subcategory. A morphism $f\colon C^{X}\to X$ is a $\mathcal{C}$-precover if $C^{X}\in\mathcal{C}$ and any other morphism $f^{\prime}\colon C^{\prime}\to X$ with $C^{\prime}\in\mathcal{C}$ factors through $f$. Dually, $g\colon X\to C_{X}$ is a $\mathcal{C}$-preenvelope if $C_{X}\in\mathcal{C}$ and any other morphism $g^{\prime}\colon X\to C^{\prime\prime}$ with $C^{\prime\prime}\in\mathcal{C}$ factors through $g$.
Definition 6.5. Let $\mathbb{D}\colon\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}^{\textrm{op}}\to\mathcal{CAT}$ be a derivator and let $\mathcal{T}=\mathbb{D}(\mathds{1})$. An object $Z\in\mathcal{T}$ is called homotopy finitely presentable if, given any directed poset $I$ and a coherent diagram $X\in\mathbb{D}(I)$, the canonical map $\varinjlim_{I}\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(Z,X_{i})\longrightarrow% \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(Z,\operatorname{hocolim}_{I}X)$ is bijective. To give more details on the construction of the morphism, consider $i\in I$, the embedding $i\colon\mathds{1}\to I$ and the projection $p\colon I\to\mathds{1}$. We can apply $i^{*}$ to the unit of adjunction $\eta\colon X\to p^{*}(\operatorname{hocolim}_{I}X)$. Since $p\circ i=\mathrm{id}_{\mathds{1}}$ and $i^{*}\circ p^{*}=\mathrm{id}_{\mathcal{T}}$, we obtain a morphism $\varepsilon_{i}\colon X_{i}\to\operatorname{hocolim}_{I}X$ in $\mathcal{T}$. It is straightforward to check that the morphisms $\varepsilon_{i}$ actually form a cocone in $\mathcal{T}$ from the direct system $(X_{i}\mid i\in I)$ to $\operatorname{hocolim}_{I}X$. It remains to apply $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(Z,-)\colon\mathcal{T}\to\mathrm{Set}$ and construct the colimit morphism in $\mathrm{Set}$.
Definition 4.7. Let $R$ be a ring and $C\in\mathrm{Mod}\textrm{-}R$ a big cotilting module. Then the tilted abelian category $\mathcal{G}$ corresponding to $C$ is defined to be the heart of the cotilting $t$-structure described in Notation 4.3. That is, $\mathcal{G}=\mathcal{D}^{\leq{0}}_{C}\cap\mathcal{D}^{\geq{0}}_{C}=\{X\in% \mathbf{D}({R})\mid\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbf{D}({R})}(X,\Sigma^{i}C)=0% \textrm{ for all }i\neq 0\}.$
Definition 3.5. A weak factorization system $(\mathcal{L},\mathcal{R})$ in an abelian category $\mathcal{A}$ is compatible with the abelian structure if the following conditions are satisfied: (FS3) $f\in\mathcal{L}$ if and only if $f$ is a monomorphism and $0\to\operatorname{Coker}f$ belongs to $\mathcal{L}$. (FS4) $g\in\mathcal{R}$ if and only if $g$ is an epimorphism and $\operatorname{Ker}f\to 0$ belongs to $\mathcal{R}$. An abelian model structure on an abelian category $\mathcal{A}$ is a model structure such that the two functorial weak factorization systems $(\mathrm{Cof}\cap\mathrm{W},\mathrm{Fib})$ and $(\mathrm{Cof},\mathrm{W}\cap\mathrm{Fib})$ are compatible with the abelian structure. An abelian model category is a complete and cocomplete abelian category together with an abelian model structure.
Definition 5.7. A functor of prederivators $F\colon\mathbb{D}\to\mathbb{D}^{\prime}$ is called an equivalence if $F_{I}\colon\mathbb{D}(I)\to\mathbb{D}(I^{\prime})$ is a usual equivalence of categories for every $I\in\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}$.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be an arbitrary category. A weak factorization system is a pair of classes of morphisms $(\mathcal{L},\mathcal{R})$ satisfying the following conditions: (FS0) $\mathcal{L}$ and $\mathcal{R}$ are closed under retracts. (FS1) Given a commutative square in $\mathcal{A}$ formed by the solid arrows of the diagram $\xymatrix{A\ar[r]\ar[d]_{f}&X\phantom{,}\ar[d]^{g}\\ B\ar[r]\ar@{.>}[ur]&Y}$ and such that $f\in\mathcal{L}$ and $g\in\mathcal{R}$, then a morphism depicted by the diagonal dotted arrow exists such that both the triangles commute. (FS2) For every morphism $h\colon X\to Y$ in $\mathcal{A}$ there exists a factorization $h=gf$ such that $f\in\mathcal{L}$ and $g\in\mathcal{R}$. We say that $(\mathcal{L},\mathcal{R})$ is a functorial weak factorization system if the factorization in (FS2) can be chosen functorially in $h$.
Definition 3.18. Let $\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B}$ be model categories, $F\colon\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{B}$ be a left adjoint functor and $U\colon\mathcal{B}\to\mathcal{A}$ be the corresponding right adjoint. Then $(F,U)$ is a Quillen pair if one of the following conditions, equivalent by [Hir03, Proposition 8.5.3], is satisfied: (1) $F$ preserves cofibrations and trivial cofibrations; (2) $U$ preserves fibrations and trivial fibrations. A Quillen pair is a pair of Quillen equivalences if it satisfies the following property: If $X\in\mathcal{A}$ is cofibrant, $Y\in\mathcal{B}$ is fibrant and $f\colon X\to U(Y)$ is a morphism in $\mathcal{A}$, then $f$ is a weak equivalence if and only if the corresponding morphism $f^{\prime}\colon F(X)\to Y$ in $\mathcal{B}$ is a weak equivalence. Equivalently by [Hov99, Proposition 1.3.13], we require that the total right derived functor $\mathbf{R}{U}\colon\operatorname{Ho}\mathcal{B}\to\operatorname{Ho}\mathcal{A}$ (see [Hir03, §8.5] for details on derived functors) is an equivalence. In such a case, $F$ is called a left Quillen equivalence and $U$ a right Quillen equivalence.
Definition 1.1. Let $\mathcal{G}$ be a Grothendieck category and $T\in\mathcal{G}$ be an object. Then $T$ is called tilting if there is a ring $R$ and a triangle equivalence $\mathbf{D}({\mathcal{G}})\longrightarrow\mathbf{D}({R})$ which sends $T$ to $R$.
Definition 3.6. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be an abelian category. A complete cotorsion pair is a pair of classes of objects $(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{F})$ such that (CP0) $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{F}$ are closed under retracts. (CP1) $\operatorname{Ext}^{1}_{\mathcal{A}}(C,F)=0$ for all $C\in\mathcal{C}$ and $F\in\mathcal{F}$. (CP2) For every object $X\in\mathcal{A}$ there exist (non-unique) short exact sequences $0\longrightarrow X\longrightarrow F_{X}\longrightarrow C_{X}\longrightarrow 0% \quad\textrm{ and }\quad 0\longrightarrow F^{X}\longrightarrow C^{X}% \longrightarrow X\longrightarrow 0$ with $C_{X},C^{X}\in\mathcal{C}$ and $F_{X},F^{X}\in\mathcal{F}$. The sequences as in (CP2) are called approximation sequences. The complete cotorsion pair is called functorially complete if the approximation short exact sequences can be chosen functorially in $X$. The complete cotorsion pair is called hereditary if $\operatorname{Ext}^{i}_{\mathcal{A}}(C,F)=0$ for all $C\in\mathcal{C}$, $F\in\mathcal{F}$ and $i>0$.
Definition 4.8 ([Bon10, Pau08]). Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a triangulated category. A co-$t$-structure on $\mathcal{T}$ is a pair of full subcategories $(\mathcal{D}_{\geq{0}},\mathcal{D}_{\leq{0}})$ which satisfies the properties (cS0)–(cS3) below. We use the notation $\mathcal{D}_{\geq{n}}=\Sigma^{-n}\mathcal{D}_{\geq{0}}$ and $\mathcal{D}_{\leq{n}}=\Sigma^{-n}\mathcal{D}_{\leq{0}}$ for each $n\in\mathbb{Z}$. (cS0) $\mathcal{D}_{\geq{0}}$ and $\mathcal{D}_{\leq{0}}$ are closed under retracts. (cS1) $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(A,B)=0$ for all $A\in\mathcal{D}_{\geq{1}}$ and $B\in\mathcal{D}_{\leq{0}}$. (cS2) $\mathcal{D}_{\geq{0}}\supseteq\mathcal{D}_{\geq{1}}$ and $\mathcal{D}_{\leq{0}}\subseteq\mathcal{D}_{\leq{1}}$. (cS3) For every object $X\in\mathcal{T}$ there exist a triangle $\tau_{\geq{1}}X\longrightarrow X\longrightarrow\tau_{\leq{0}}X\longrightarrow% \Sigma\tau_{\geq{1}}X.$ The coheart of the co-$t$-structure is the full subcategory $\mathcal{I}=\mathcal{D}_{\geq{0}}\cap\mathcal{D}_{\leq{0}}$ of $\mathcal{T}$.
Definition 1.13. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a triangulated category with small coproducts and let $Z\in\mathcal{T}$ be a compact object. A Brown-Comenetz dual of $Z$ in $\mathcal{T}$ is an object $\mathbb{BC}({Z})\in\mathcal{T}$ such that there exists a natural equivalence $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}\big{(}-,\mathbb{BC}({Z})\big{)}\overset{\cong% }{\longrightarrow}\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}\big{(}\operatorname{Hom}_{% \mathcal{T}}(Z,-),\mathbb{Q}/\mathbb{Z}\big{)}$ of functors $\mathcal{T}^{\textrm{op}}\to\mathrm{Ab}$.
Definition 5.9 ([CN08, Gro12, Gro91, Mal07]). A prederivator $\mathbb{D}\colon\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}^{\textrm{op}}\to\mathcal{CAT}$ is a derivator if it satisfies the axioms (Der1)–(Der4) below. (Der1) Given a set $S$ and a collection $(I_{s}\mid s\in S)$ of small categories, the canonical functor $\mathbb{D}\Big{(}\coprod_{s\in S}I_{S}\Big{)}\longrightarrow\prod_{s\in S}% \mathbb{D}(X_{s})$ is an equivalence of categories. (Der2) Let $I\in\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}$ and $f\colon X\to Y$ be a morphism in $\mathbb{D}(I)$. Then $f$ is an isomorphism if and only if $f_{i}\colon X_{i}\to Y_{i}$ is an isomorphism for each $i\in I$. (Der3) Given a functor $u\colon I\to J$ in $\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}$, then $u^{*}\colon\mathbb{D}(J)\to\mathbb{D}(I)$ has both a left adjoint $u_{!}\colon\mathbb{D}(I)\to\mathbb{D}(J)$ and a right adjoint $u_{*}\colon\mathbb{D}(I)\to\mathbb{D}(J)$ If $J=\mathds{1}$ and $p\colon I\to\mathds{1}$ is the unique functor, it is common to use special notation and terminology. The functor $p_{!}\colon\mathbb{D}(I)\to\mathbb{D}(\mathds{1})$ is denoted by $\operatorname{hocolim}_{I}$ and called the homotopy colimit functor, while $p_{*}$ is denoted by $\operatorname{holim}_{I}$ and is called the homotopy limit functor. (Der4) Given a functor $u\colon I\to J$ in $\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}$ and objects $X\in\mathbb{D}(I)$ and $i\in I$, there are base change formulas which allow to canonically identify $u_{!}(X)_{i}$ and $u_{*}(X)_{i}$ with homotopy colimits and limits of certain comma categories, respectively. Rather than giving the details here, we refer to [Mal07, §2], [CN08, Definition 1.11] or [Gro12, Definition 1.10]. The derivator $\mathbb{D}$ is called strong if it in addition satisfies (Der5) The partial diagram functors $d_{[1],I}\colon\mathbb{D}([1]\times I)\to\mathbb{D}(I)^{[1]}$ are full and essentially surjective for all $I\in\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}$.
Definition 1.3. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a triangulated category with small coproducts. An object $Z\in\mathcal{T}$ is compact if, given any small collection $(X_{i}\mid i\in I)$ of objects of $\mathcal{T}$, the canonical homomorphism of abelian groups $\coprod_{i}\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(Z,X_{i})\longrightarrow% \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}\Big{(}Z,\coprod_{i}X_{i}\Big{)}$ is an isomorphism. Equivalently, every morphism $Z\to\coprod_{i}X_{i}$ in $\mathcal{T}$ has only finitely many non-zero components. An object $Z\in\mathcal{T}$ is a generator of $\mathcal{T}$ (in the triangulated sense) if, given a non-zero object $0\neq X\in\mathcal{T}$, there exists $i\in\mathbb{Z}$ such that $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(\Sigma^{i}Z,X)\neq 0$.
Definition 3.20. Let $C$ be a big cotilting module over a ring $R$. Then the cotilting class associated with $C$ is defined as $\mathcal{X}_{C}=\{X\in\mathrm{Mod}\textrm{-}R\mid\operatorname{Ext}^{i}_{R}(X,% C)=0\textrm{ for all }i>0\}.$
Definition 5.16. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be an abelian category and let $\mathbb{D}_{\mathcal{A}}$ be the prederivator as in Construction 5.2. A full subcategory $\mathcal{E}\subseteq\mathcal{A}$ which is functorially resolving and such that the $\mathcal{E}$-resolution dimension of objects of $\mathcal{A}$ is bounded by some $n\in\mathbb{N}$, is called a blueprint for $\mathbb{D}_{\mathcal{A}}$. If $\mathcal{E}$ is functorially coresolving and the $\mathcal{E}$-coresolution dimension is uniformly bounded, $\mathcal{E}$ is called the dual blueprint for $\mathbb{D}_{\mathcal{A}}$.
Definition 3.3. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a model category. An object $X\in\mathcal{A}$ is called cofibrant if the unique morphism $0\to X$ from the initial object $0\in\mathcal{A}$ is a cofibration. Dually, $X$ is fibrant if the unique morphism $X\to*$ to a terminal object $*\in X$ is a fibration. If $\mathcal{A}$ is a pointed category (the unique morphism $0\to*$ is an isomorphism), then $X$ is called trivial if $0\to X$ is a weak equivalence.
Definition 1.6 ([AHC01]). Let $R$ be a ring, $C$ a right $R$-module and $n\geq 0$. Then $C$ is a big $n$-cotilting module if it satisfies the following three conditions: (BC1) $C$ has injective dimension bounded by $n$. That is there exists an exact sequence in $\mathrm{Mod}\textrm{-}R$ of the form $0\longrightarrow C\longrightarrow E_{0}\longrightarrow E_{1}\longrightarrow% \cdots\longrightarrow E_{n}\longrightarrow 0$ with all the $E_{i}$ injective. (BC2) $\operatorname{Ext}^{j}_{R}(C^{I},C)=0$ for every $j>0$ and every set $I$. Here, $C^{I}$ is the product of copies of $C$ indexed by $I$. (BC3) There exists an exact sequence $0\longrightarrow C_{r}\longrightarrow\dots\longrightarrow C_{1}\longrightarrow C% _{0}\longrightarrow Q\longrightarrow 0$ in $\mathrm{Mod}\textrm{-}R$ such that $Q$ is an injective cogenerator of $\mathrm{Mod}\textrm{-}R$, $r\geq 0$ and $C_{i}\in\operatorname{Prod}C$ for all $i$. Moreover, $C$ is called big cotilting if it is big $n$-cotilting for some $n\geq 0$.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be an abelian category and $\mathcal{X}\subseteq\mathcal{A}$ be a full subcategory. Then $\mathcal{X}$ is a resolving subcategory if it satisfies the following. (R0) $\mathcal{X}$ is closed under retracts. (R1) Suppose that $0\to X\to Y\to Z\to 0$ is a short exact sequence and $Z\in\mathcal{X}$. Then $X\in\mathcal{X}$ if and only if $Y\in\mathcal{X}$. (R2) $\mathcal{X}$ is generating. That is, for any $A\in\mathcal{A}$ there exists an epimorphism $X\to A$ with $X\in\mathcal{X}$. A resolving subcategory is called functorially resolving provided that the epimorphisms in (R2) can be taken functorially in $A$. The resolution dimension of an object $A\in\mathcal{A}$ with respect to $\mathcal{X}$, denoted $\operatorname{res.dim}_{\mathcal{X}}A$, is defined as the smallest integer $n\geq 0$ such that there exists an exact sequence $0\longrightarrow X_{n}\longrightarrow\cdots\longrightarrow X_{1}% \longrightarrow X_{0}\longrightarrow A\longrightarrow 0$ with $X_{0},X_{1},\dots,X_{n}\in\mathcal{X}$, or $\operatorname{res.dim}_{\mathcal{X}}A=\infty$ if such $n$ does not exist. Coresolving and functorially coresolving subcategories and coresolution dimension are defined dually.
Definition 3.11. A (functorially) complete cotorsion pair in a Grothendieck category which occurs as in Proposition 3.10 is said to be generated by a small set.
Definition 5.4. A $1$-morphism (or simply a morphism) $F\colon\mathbb{D}\to\mathbb{D}^{\prime}$ of prederivators is given by the following data: (1) A collection of functors $F_{I}\colon\mathbb{D}(I)\to\mathbb{D}^{\prime}(I)$, one for each $I\in\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}$. (2) A collection of natural equivalences $\gamma_{u}\colon u^{*}\circ F_{J}\Rightarrow F_{I}\circ u^{*}$ indexed by $1$-morphisms $u\colon I\to J$ in $\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}$. That is, we have squares of functors $\begin{CD}\mathbb{D}(J)@>{F_{J}}>{}>\mathbb{D}^{\prime}(J)\\ @V{u^{*}}V{}V@V{}V{u^{*}}V\\ \mathbb{D}(I)@>{F_{I}}>{}>\mathbb{D}^{\prime}(I)\\ \end{CD}$ commutative up to the equivalence $\gamma_{u}$. This datum is required to satisfy the following three coherence conditions. Given a pair of composable functors $I\overset{u}{\to}J\overset{v}{\to}K$ in $\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}$ and a natural transformation $\alpha\colon u_{1}\Rightarrow u_{2}$ between $u_{1},u_{2}\colon I\to J$ in $\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}$, we have the equalities (a) $\gamma_{\mathrm{id}_{J}}=\mathrm{id}_{F_{J}}$ as transformations $F_{J}\Rightarrow F_{J}$, (b) $\gamma_{v\circ u}=\gamma_{u}v^{*}\circ u^{*}\gamma_{v}$ as transformations $u^{*}\circ v^{*}\circ F_{K}\Rightarrow F_{I}\circ u^{*}\circ v^{*}$, and (c) $F_{I}\alpha^{*}\circ\gamma_{u_{1}}=\gamma_{u_{2}}\circ\alpha^{*}F_{J}$ as transformations $u_{1}^{*}\circ F_{J}\Rightarrow F_{I}\circ u_{2}^{*}$. If $F,G\colon\mathbb{D}\to\mathbb{D}^{\prime}$ are two morphisms of prederivators, a $2$-morphism (or a natural transformation) $\tau\colon F\Rightarrow G$ is collection of natural transformations $\tau_{I}\colon F_{I}\to G_{I}$, where $I$ runs over small categories, satisfying the following compatibility condition. Given a functor $u\colon I\to J$ in $\mathcal{C}\mathnormal{at}$, then $\tau_{I}u^{*}\circ\gamma_{u}^{F}=\gamma_{u}^{G}\circ u^{*}\tau_{J}$ as transformations $u^{*}\circ F_{J}\Rightarrow G_{I}\circ u^{*}$, where the superscripts at $\gamma_{u}$ distinguish the transformation which is a part of the defining datum of $F$ from the one belonging to $G$.
Definition 4.1. An $\infty$-category is stable [HA, 1.1.1.9] if it has finite limits and colimits and pushout and pullback squares coincide [HA, 1.1.3.4]. Let $Cat_{\infty}^{ex}$ denote the $\infty$-category of small stable $\infty$-categories and exact functors (i.e., functors which preserve finite limits and colimits) [HA, 1.1.4]. The $\infty$-category of exact functors between $A$ and $B$ is denoted by $Fun^{ex}(A,B)$.
Definition 2.24. The model category structure defined above will be referred to as the Morita model category structure on $Cat_{dg}^{k}$.
Definition 4.15. A morphism $f$ in an $\infty$-operad $p:\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}\to N(\Gamma)$ is called inert if $p(f)$ is inert and $f$ is p-coCartesian.
Definition 2.18. A dg functor $\mathcal{F}:\mathcal{T}\to\mathcal{T}^{\prime}$ is a Dwyer-Kan embedding or DK-embedding if for any objects $x,y\in Ob(\mathcal{T})$, the map $\mathcal{T}(x,y)\to\mathcal{T}^{\prime}(\mathcal{F}(x),\mathcal{F}(y))$ is a quasi-isomorphism.
Definition 2.3. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a dg category. The homotopy category of $\mathcal{T}$, denoted by $[\mathcal{T}]$, is the ordinary category given by: • The objects of $[\mathcal{T}]$, $Ob([\mathcal{T}])$, are the objects of $\mathcal{T}$. • For every pair of objects $x,y\in Ob([\mathcal{T}])$, the set of morphisms $[\mathcal{T}](x,y):=H^{0}(\mathcal{T}(x,y)$.
Definition 4.21. Applying [HA, 2.1.1.7] to the colored operad $\mathbb{LM}$, we obtain a category $\mathbb{LM}^{\otimes}$ and a map $\mathbb{LM}^{\otimes}\to\Gamma$. Thus, the nerve $\mathcal{L}\mathcal{M}^{\otimes}:=N(\mathbb{LM}^{\otimes})\to N(\Gamma)$ is the $\infty$-operad which controls left module objects over an associative algebra. There is also an $\infty$-operad $\mathcal{A}ss^{\otimes}$ obtained by applying the same construction to $\mathbb{Ass}$.
Definition 2.1. A differential graded (dg) category $\mathcal{T}$ over $k$ consists of the following data. • A class of objects $Ob(\mathcal{T})$. • For every pair of objects $x,y\in\mathcal{T}$ a complex $\mathcal{T}(x,y)\in Ch(k)$. • For every triple $x,y,z\in\mathcal{T}$ a composition $\mathcal{T}(y,z)\otimes\mathcal{T}(x,y)\to\mathcal{T}(x,z)$. • A unit for every $x\in\mathcal{T}$, $e_{x}:k\to\mathcal{T}(x,x)$ These data are required to satisfy the usual associativity and unit conditions.
Definition 2.14. A dg category $\mathcal{T}$ is called pretriangulated if (1) There is an object $0$ in $\mathcal{T}$ such that the right $\mathcal{T}$-module $\mathcal{T}(-,0)$ is homotopically trivial (weakly equivalent to the constant functor with value the complex $0$). (2) Whenever a right $\mathcal{T}$-module $M$ has the property that $\Sigma M$ is weakly equivalent to a representable $\mathcal{T}$-module $\mathcal{T}(-,c)$ (for some object $c\in\mathcal{T}$), then $M$ is weakly equivalent to a representable $\mathcal{T}$-module $\mathcal{T}(-,d)$ for some object $d\in\mathcal{T}$. (The suspension of a $\mathcal{T}$-module $M$ refers to a pointwise shift when evaluated on each object of $\mathcal{T}$). (3) Whenever the right $\mathcal{T}$-modules $M$ and $N$ are weakly equivalent to representable $\mathcal{T}$-modules $\mathcal{T}(-,a)$ and $\mathcal{T}(-,b)$ respectively, the homotopy cofiber of any map of right $\mathcal{T}$-modules $M\to N$ is weakly equivalent to a representable $\mathcal{T}$-module.
Definition 4.5. Let $\langle n\rangle^{\circ}=\{1,2,\ldots,n\}$, we will say a morphism $f:\langle m\rangle\to\langle n\rangle$ is inert if for $i\in\langle n\rangle^{\circ}$, the inverse image $f^{-1}(i)$ has exactly one element.
Definition 4.17. If $p:\mathcal{C}^{\otimes}\to\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}$ is a fibration of $\infty$-operads (i.e. a categorical fibration [T, 2.2.5.1]) and $f:\mathcal{O}^{\prime\otimes}\to\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}$ is a map of $\infty$-operads, let $Alg_{\mathcal{O}^{\prime}/\mathcal{O}}(\mathcal{C})$ be the full subcategory of $Fun_{\mathcal{O}}(\mathcal{O}^{\prime\otimes},\mathcal{C}^{\otimes})$ spanned by the maps of $\infty$-operads. When $\mathcal{O}=\mathcal{O}^{\prime}$ and $f$ is the identity, we will denote this $\infty$-category by $Alg_{\mathcal{O}}(\mathcal{C})$, the $\infty$-category of $\mathcal{O}$-algebra objects in $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 3.2. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a spectral category. The homotopy category of $\mathcal{A}$, denoted by $[\mathcal{A}]$, is the ordinary category given by: • The objects of $[\mathcal{A}]$, $Ob([\mathcal{A}])$, are the objects of $\mathcal{A}$. • For every pair of objects $x,y\in Ob([\mathcal{A}])$, the set of morphisms $[\mathcal{A}](x,y):=\pi_{0}(\mathcal{T}(x,y))$.
Definition 4.23. A spectral category C is pointwise-cofibrant if each morphism spectrum $C(x,y)$ is a cofibrant spectrum.
Definition 3.7. An $R$-module $M$ is called cell if $M$ is the union of an expanding sequence of sub $R$-modules $M_{l}$ such that $M_{0}=*$ and $M_{j+1}$ is the homotopy cofiber of a map $\phi_{j}:F_{j}\to M_{j}$, where $F_{j}$ is a wedge of shifts of $R$ as a module over itself. We denote the category of cell $R$-modules by $R-Mod^{cell}$.
Definition 2.21. Given a dg category $\mathcal{T}$, its triangulated closure, $\hat{\mathcal{T}}_{tri}$, is defined to be the dg subcategory in $\hat{\mathcal{T}}^{cf}$ of objects that have the homotopy type of finite cell objects. Given a dg category $\mathcal{T}$, the category of perfect modules, $\hat{\mathcal{T}}_{perf}$, is the thick closure of $\hat{\mathcal{T}}_{tri}$. That is, it is the smallest full dg subcategory of $\hat{\mathcal{T}}$ containing objects that have the homotopy type of retracts of finite cell objects.
Definition 4.10. An $\infty$-operad is an $\infty$-category $\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}$ and a functor $p:\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}\to N(\Gamma)$ satisfying the following conditions [HA, 2.1.1.10]: • The map $p$ is a coCartesian fibration. Thus, for every inert morphism $f:\langle m\rangle\to\langle n\rangle$ in $\Gamma$ and every object $C\in\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}_{\langle m\rangle}$, there is a p-coCartesian morphism $\tilde{f}:C\to C^{\prime}$ in $\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}$ lifting $f$. • Let $C\in\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}_{\langle m\rangle}$ and $C^{\prime}\in\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}_{\langle n\rangle}$ be objects, let $f:\langle m\rangle\to\langle n\rangle$ be a morphism in $\Gamma$, and let $map^{f}_{\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}}(C,C^{\prime})$ denote the union of the components of $map_{\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}}(C,C^{\prime})$ which lie over $f\in Hom_{\Gamma}(\langle m\rangle,\langle n\rangle)$. Choose $p$-coCartesian morphisms $C^{\prime}\to C^{\prime}_{i}$ lying over the morphism $\rho^{i}:\langle n\rangle\to\langle 1\rangle$ for each $1\leq i\leq n$. The the induced map $map^{f}_{\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}}(C,C^{\prime})\to\prod_{i}map^{f\circ\rho^{i}}_% {\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}}(C,C^{\prime}_{i})$ is a homotopy equivalence. • For every finite collection $C_{1},C_{2},\ldots,C_{n}$ of $\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}_{\langle 1\rangle}$, there exists an object $C$ of $\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}_{\langle n\rangle}$ and $p$-coCartesian morphisms $C\to C_{i}$ covering each $\rho^{i}$.
Definition 2.11. Given a dg category $\mathcal{T}$ the category of $\mathcal{T}$-modules, $\hat{\mathcal{T}}$ is defined to be $Fun_{dg}(\mathcal{T}^{op},Ch(k))$. That is, a $\mathcal{T}$-module is a functor from $\mathcal{T}^{op}\to Ch(k)$.
Definition 3.6. Let $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ be two spectral categories. The smash product $\mathcal{C}\wedge\mathcal{D}$ is the spectral category specified by • The objects of $\mathcal{C}\wedge\mathcal{D}$, $Ob(\mathcal{C}\wedge\mathcal{D})$, are given by pairs of objects $(c,d)$, where $c\in\mathcal{C}$ and $d\in\mathcal{D}$. • For every pair of objects $(c,d),(c^{\prime},d^{\prime})\in\mathcal{C}\wedge\mathcal{D}$, the morphism spectrum $\mathcal{C}\wedge\mathcal{D}((c,d),(c^{\prime},d^{\prime}):=\mathcal{C}(c,c^{% \prime})\wedge\mathcal{D}(d,d^{\prime})$.
Definition 4.9. Let $p:X\to S$ be an inner fibration of simplicial sets, $p$ is a coCartesian fibration of simplicial sets if for every edge $\bar{f}:s\to s^{\prime}$ in $S$, and every vertex $x\in X$ with $p(x)=s$, there exists a $p$-coCartesian edge $f:x\to x^{\prime}$ with $p(f)=\bar{f}$.
Definition 2.20. Given a dg category $\mathcal{T}$, a $\mathcal{T}$-module $X:\mathcal{T}^{op}\to Ch(k)$ is called a finite cell object if it can be obtained from the initial $\mathcal{T}$-module by a finite sequence of pushouts along generating cofibrations in $\hat{\mathcal{T}}$.
Definition 4.16. A morphism of $\infty$-operads is a map of simplicial sets $f:\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}\to\mathcal{O}^{\prime\otimes}$ over $N(\Gamma)$ such that $f$ takes inert morphisms in $\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}$ to inert morphisms in $\mathcal{O}^{\prime\otimes}$. The $\infty$-category of $\infty$-operad maps is denoted $Alg_{\mathcal{O}}(\mathcal{O}^{\prime})$ and is considered as a full subcategory of $Fun_{N(\Gamma)}(\mathcal{O}^{\otimes},\mathcal{O}^{\prime\otimes})$.
Definition 3.1. A spectral category $\mathcal{A}$ is given by • A class of objects $Ob(\mathcal{A})$. • For each pair of objects $x,y\in Ob(\mathcal{A})$, a symmetric spectrum $\mathcal{A}(x,y)$. • For each triple $x,y,z\in Ob(\mathcal{A})$ a composition in $\mathcal{S}$, $\mathcal{A}(y,z)\wedge\mathcal{A}(x,y)\to\mathcal{A}(x,z)$. • For any $x\in Ob(\mathcal{A})$, a map $e_{x}:\mathbb{S}\to\mathcal{A}(x,x)$ in $\mathcal{S}$. satisfying the usual associativity and unit conditions.
Definition 4.3. Let $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ be small stable $\infty$-categories. Then we will say that $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ are Morita equivalent if $Idem(\mathcal{A})$ and $Idem(\mathcal{B})$ are equivalent.
Definition 4.22. Let $\mathcal{C}^{\otimes}\to\mathcal{A}ss^{\otimes}$ be a fibration of $\infty$-operads, and $\mathcal{M}$ and $\infty$-category. A weak enrichment of $\mathcal{M}$ over $\mathcal{C}^{\otimes}$ is a fibration of $\infty$-operads $q:\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}\to\mathcal{L}\mathcal{M}^{\otimes}$ such that $\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}_{\mathbb{a}}\simeq\mathcal{C}^{\otimes}$ and $\mathcal{O}^{\otimes}_{\mathbb{m}}\simeq\mathcal{M}$. We let $LMod(\mathcal{M}):=Alg_{\mathcal{L}\mathcal{M}}(\mathcal{O})$ be the $\infty$-category of left module objects in the $\infty$-category $\mathcal{M}$ [HA, 4.2.1.13].
Definition 2.2. Let $\mathcal{T}$ and $\mathcal{T}^{\prime}$ be dg categories. A dg functor $\mathcal{F}:\mathcal{T}\to\mathcal{T}^{\prime}$ consists of: • A map on objects $\mathcal{F}:Ob(\mathcal{T})\to Ob(\mathcal{T}^{\prime})$. • A map of chain complexes $\mathcal{F}_{x,y}:\mathcal{T}(x,y)\to\mathcal{T}^{\prime}(\mathcal{F}(x),% \mathcal{F}(y))$ for all $x,y\in Ob(\mathcal{T})$, which is compatible with the units and compositions in the obvious sense.
Definition 2.23. A dg functor $\mathcal{F}:\mathcal{T}\to\mathcal{T}^{\prime}$ is called a Morita equivalence if $\mathcal{F}$ induces a DK-equivalence of dg categories $\hat{\mathcal{T}}_{perf}\to\hat{\mathcal{T}^{\prime}}_{perf}$.
Definition 4.13. A symmetric monoidal $\infty$-category [HA, 2.1.2.18] is an $\infty$-category $\mathcal{C}$ and a coCartesian fibration of $\infty$-operads $p:\mathcal{C}^{\otimes}\to N(\Gamma)$. The underlying $\infty$-category $\mathcal{C}$ is obtained by $\mathcal{C}=p^{-1}(\langle 1\rangle)$. In abuse of terminology, we say that $\mathcal{C}$ is a symmetric monoidal $\infty$-category.
Definition 2.17. To a dg category $\mathcal{A}$, Bondal and Kapranov associate another dg category, $\mathcal{A}^{pre-tr}$, where the objects are formal expressions $\{(\oplus_{i=1}^{n}C_{i}[r_{i}],q),C_{i}\in\mathcal{A},r_{i}\in\mathbb{Z},q=(q% _{ij})\},$ where each $q_{ij}\in Hom(C_{i},C_{j})[r_{j}-r_{i}]$ is homogenous of degree 1 and $dq+q^{2}=0$. If $C,C^{\prime}\in\mathcal{A}^{pre-tr}$, $C=(\oplus_{j=1}^{n}C_{j}[r_{j}],q)$ and $C^{\prime}=(\oplus_{i=1}^{n}C^{\prime}_{i}[r^{\prime}_{i}],q^{\prime})$, then the complex $Hom(C,C^{\prime})$ is the space of matrices $f=(f_{ij}),f_{ij}\in Hom(C_{j},C^{\prime}_{i})[r^{\prime}_{i}-r_{j}]$ and composition is given by matrix multiplication. The differential $d:Hom(C,C^{\prime})\to Hom(C,C^{\prime})$ is given by $df:=d^{\prime}f+q^{\prime}f-(-1)^{l}fq,\mbox{ if deg}(f_{ij})=l,$ where $d^{\prime}:=(df_{ij})$. Given a morphism $f:A\to B$ in $\mathcal{A}$, the cone on f, $cone(f)$, is defined to be the object $(A[1]\oplus B,q)\in A^{pre-tr}$, where $q_{12}=f$ and $q_{11}=q_{21}=q_{22}=0$. The dg category $\mathcal{A}$ is said to be pretriangulated if $0\in\mathcal{A}^{pre-tr}$ is homotopic to an object in $\mathcal{A}$, if for every $A\in\mathcal{A}$, the object $A[n]\in A^{pre-tr}$, is homotopic to an object in $\mathcal{A}$, and for every closed morphism $f$ of degree 0 in $\mathcal{A}$, $cone(f)\in\mathcal{A}^{pre-tr}$, is homotopic to an object in $\mathcal{A}$.
